What do we do now?

As we approach the 2024 Presidential election, we have much to consider.  The current media “experts” continually pound our heads with their polarizing diatribe.  The “left” has all the facts and numbers to back up their campaign against Trump.  Their data is irrefutable.   The “right” also back up their claims with absolute facts and assumptions against Biden. Their arguments are also irrefutable.  At the same time both can dig up any quote or occasion or video clip to depict the other candidate as a despot.   All social factions with their media jump on the current bandwagon or disaster or issue or non-issue or war or public gaff or protest, or broken law to point their finger at the “other” side.    Even the assassination attempt has been used by both parties and media to promote or defame the other.  These claims by both parties are many times heavily biased and false with a sprinkling of truth.  Just enough to keep many Americans in a state of “Huh?’  We end up like sheep being driven back and forth.  The irony is that we have better leaders in our country than either of these two pugilists.  Our problems and issues in this country will not be remedied by either of these two in the next four years.  Why? Because neither side will accept the outcome.  We will have four more years of toxic hatred and animosity.  To make it even more alarming, they will take their extreme followers with them.  As Trump stated, “there will be blood in the streets”!  Many of the issues are culture differences and are solvable at least through some compromise.  Open our eyes and realize the bigger issues such as national debt, health, economy, immigration and crime will not be solved by the two major players.  Together they created or at least promoted some of these issues.  A quote by Mia Angelo applies to both men.  “When people show you who they are. Believe them the first time.”
What do we do?  Personally, I cannot support either of the predominate candidates.  Their records speak for them.  Their continued personal attacks in lieu of substantive solutions to things that matter promotes a nation of hate and turmoil.   That will not end with Biden or Trump!  I see major chinks in their moral character.  Even if many of the lies thrown at both candidates are only half truths.   They both have demonstrated character that continues to fester in their respective political parties.  What do we do?   
My path is clear to me, and I respect your personal path.   As part of the silent majority, I cannot stomach four more years reflecting on what has transpired in the past.  Right, wrong or indifferent, change must come to our country.   Again, don’t vilify me for my personal beliefs.  The only solution for me is Robert F Kennedy, Jr.. Kennedy has made a point of leaving personalities out of his discussions concerning his political adversaries.  Even as Trump/Biden attack him at every turn. I believe, regardless of some of his policies and platforms, that he really would work to bring a semblance of unity to the country.  Kennedy is smarter than the other two.  He does not flaunt religion as a political tool. He admits his past mistakes and will change his position if he has the facts to do so.  If you like the Kennedys or not, his background makes him a unique candidate.  Can he solve all our social and national issues?  Probably not! But at least we won’t spin our wheels for the next four years.  Progress will be made. The other two are known quantities, Kennedy presents a fresh start.  Maybe the last chance for some positive change. So, be willing to listen to him.  Even if he doesn’t check all your boxes, neither do the other two.  Vote for positive progress!

"We do not agree on everything, but we all adhere to two fundamental principles," the letters states. "First, we believe America’s national security requires a serious and capable Commander-in-Chief. Second, we believe American democracy is invaluable. Each generation has a responsibility to defend it. That is why we, the undersigned, proudly endorse Kamala Harris to be the next President of the United States."
Among the signatories are Rear Admiral Michael E. Smith (Ret); Lieutenant General Charles D. Luckey (Ret); Caroline Atkinson, former Deputy National Security Advisor to President Obama; and John Brennan, former Director of the CIA.

Addressing Illegal Immigration: Why U.S. Solutions Should Focus on Border Security, Not Fixing Other Countries’ Problems

The issue of illegal immigration is complex and multifaceted, with roots deeply embedded in factors such as unemployment, poverty, cartel violence, drug trafficking, smuggling, and political corruption in countries of origin. While former President Donald Trump’s approach, which emphasizes stringent border security and deportation, addresses immediate U.S. concerns, it's important to recognize that the underlying causes of illegal immigration are not solely America's responsibility.

The Limits of U.S. Responsibility
The suggestion that the United States should address the systemic problems in other countries—such as economic instability, drug cartels, and political corruption—oversimplifies the issue and places an unreasonable burden on U.S. policy. The root causes of illegal immigration are complex and deeply entrenched in the domestic issues of other nations. Unemployment, poverty, and violence in these countries drive individuals to seek opportunities elsewhere, often leading them to attempt illegal entry into the U.S.

The Focus on Border Security
Trump’s solution to illegal immigration, which includes securing the border and deporting illegal immigrants, reflects a common-sense approach to managing the direct impacts of illegal immigration on the U.S. This approach prioritizes protecting American borders and ensuring that those who enter illegally, particularly those involved in criminal activities, are addressed. It’s a pragmatic response to immediate concerns, rather than an attempt to solve the broader, more entrenched problems in other countries.

The Role of Other Nations
It is crucial for other nations to take responsibility for addressing the root causes of migration. Efforts to combat poverty, improve economic conditions, and tackle corruption are essential in reducing the factors that drive people to leave their home countries. U.S. foreign policy can support these efforts through targeted aid and cooperation, but the primary responsibility for addressing these issues lies with the countries experiencing them.

A Practical Approach
Focusing U.S. immigration policy on strengthening border security and managing illegal immigration effectively is a practical approach to handling the immediate challenges faced. Addressing the root causes of migration requires international cooperation and support, but it should not be conflated with U.S. immigration policies or viewed as the sole responsibility of the United States. Managing Immediate Concerns with Realistic Solutions
The challenge of illegal immigration is undeniably influenced by factors outside U.S. control, including socioeconomic and political issues in other countries. While it is important for the U.S. to engage in supportive measures internationally, it is equally important for domestic policies to focus on practical solutions to manage illegal immigration effectively. Trump’s approach, which emphasizes border security and the removal of illegal immigrants, addresses immediate concerns without suggesting that the U.S. should be responsible for fixing systemic problems in other countries.
